text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Title: Tone Systems: Comparing English and Mandarin%0a:Author: BenP%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 20.02.2021 - 15:32%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-214917-235860#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 14:49-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-214917-235860#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI consider the similarities between intonation and tone and question how they developed.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aA tonal language is one which contains words that are only distinguished by the tone of pronunciation. The same collection of letters in a tonal language can mean two different words depending on how the speaker emphasizes the syllables. Mandarin is one example of a tonal language, while English is not.%0a%0aAs an English speaker and not a Mandarin speaker, I find that it would be difficult to learn Mandarin because regulating tone for individual syllables would be hard for me. I am more used to navigating intonation, which can change the meaning of sentences rather than words. For example, in class, we looked at the example, "GIOVANNI said that Olga went to the store" vs "Giovanni said that OLGA went to the store" (I'm using caps for italics). In this example, its clear that the important information, such as the answer to the question of "Who said that Olga went to the store?" or "Who went to the store?" is emphasized. Still, it is possible to convey the same information, only less dramatically, without changing intonation.%0a%0aIt seems to me that intonation and tone are related in this way. Meaning is emphasized and conveyed, respectively, by the sound of the speaker. Tone seems like a continuation of intonation in this way. In considering how languages develop, I wonder whether intonation progressed into tone systems in tonal languages, intonation developed from tone, or if the two progressed independently of each other.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
